      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0ed3873839928594",
        "text": "The equilibrium model, at any rate, establishes a strand of developments toward a general systems theory. However, this was not a new discovery in the 1950s, but only a variant to which one could fall back if necessary. New were two other sets of problems, which then influenced the further development of systems theory more strongly than this equilibrium theory. New was above all the question, coming from thermodynamics, how systems can be preserved at all, if one has to assume that physics, at least the physics of closed systems, tends to generate entropy, i.e. to dissolve all distinctions, to bring about a distinctionless state or, physically speaking, to bring about a state in which there is no more usable energy, i.e. no energy that can generate any distinctions. If this is a general physical law, how is it possible to explain the facts of the physical, chemical, biological, social world at all? How is it possible to explain that there is order and that, limiting the perspective to a few billion years, one cannot see that such a development towards entropy is actually taking place? In other words, how is negentropy to be explained as a deviation from the state of entropy, when the laws of physics in themselves run toward entropy? In this question one had in mind that the entropy laws presuppose a closed system, and one imagined, for example, the world as a closed system into which nothing enters from the outside and from which nothing can be led out from the inside."
      },
